28-year-old cook found dead in San Francisco shopping mall
A 28-year-old chef who recently moved to San Francisco was found dead in the stairwell of a local mall this week.
However, the victim’s brother says he can’t imagine someone wanting to hurt him, noting, “He’s finally got things in order.”
"The body found in Westfield Mall on Wednesday morning was identified as 28-year-old San Francisco resident Frank Galicia," the San Francisco Bureau of Forensic Medicine said in a statement.
The San Francisco Police Department reports that the death has been classified as murder and the investigation is ongoing.
The victim's brother, Luis Galicia, told ABC's KGO TV in San Francisco that Frank, a past delivery line cook in Boston, got his dream job as a chef at San Francisco's Sons & Daughters restaurant six months ago.
Sons & Daughters said they were "shocked and crushed" by his death.
“We are a small team that works as a friendly family and will be greatly missed,” the representative said.
Our thoughts and condolences to Frank's family and friends during this difficult time.
Luis Galicia said that Frank first stayed in hostels, but lately "he's finally got things in order."
“He found an apartment, he was dating a girl,” Luis Galicia told KGO.
Luis Galicia said he couldn’t imagine anyone wanting to hurt his younger brother.
He had a good heart and a good heart.
His way of connecting with the family has always been to prepare some dish for us, to prepare dinner for us,” said Luis Galicia.
He never wanted to be involved in a fight.
He was a brother who was swimming in the stream.
“Despite all the bad things that happen to this world, it was that pristine diamond that shone brightly every day,” he said.
All those who have the information are asked to call the SFPD Hotline at 415-575-4444.
