Scientists have found an animal that can live 500 years
An international group of biologists has concluded that the longest-lived vertebrate is the Greenlandic polar shark, which can live for about 500 years.
Scientists conducted a radiocarbon analysis of the eye crystals of 28 Greenland sharks.
The largest shark, the length of which exceeds five meters, can be from 272 to 512 years.
Biologists believe that a low metabolism plays an important role in the longevity of the shark, which leads to slow development.
The females of Greenland sharks reach sexual maturity only by 150 years.
Previously, it was believed that the longest of all vertebrate animals lives "neighbor" of the shark - the Greenlandic whale.
The oldest person known to scientists was just over 210 years old.
