Head of the administration of the President of the Russian Federation Anton Vaino.
On Friday, August 12, Vladimir Putin appointed Anton Vaino as the head of the Russian presidential administration.
This position was previously held by Sergey Ivanov.
"The head of state appointed Anton Vaino as the head of the administration of the President of the Russian Federation by his decree, releasing him from office," the decree signed by Putin and published on the Kremlin's website said.
Since May 2012, Vaino has been deputy head of the administration of the President of the Russian Federation.
Anton Eduardovich Vaino was born on February 17, 1972 in Tallinn.
The father is Eduard Vaino, Chairman of the Cuba-Russia Business Council in the Chamber of Commerce and Industry of the Russian Federation and Vice-President for External Relations and Cooperation with the shareholders of AvtoVAZ.
Grandfather - Karl Vaino - from 1978 to 1988 the first secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Estonia.
In 1996 he graduated from the Moscow State Institute of International Relations of the Russian Foreign Ministry, the Faculty of International Relations.
From 1996 to 2001 he worked at the Russian Embassy in Japan, then at the Second Department of Asia of the Russian Foreign Ministry.
From 2002 to 2004, he held various positions in the Office of the President of the Russian Federation.
From 2004 to 2007 - Deputy Head of the Protocol and Organizational Department of the President of the Russian Federation.
From 2007 to 2007 - the first deputy head of protocol of the President of the Russian Federation.
From October 2007 to April 2008 - Deputy Head of the Government of the Russian Federation.
On April 25, 2008, he was appointed as the head of protocol of the President of the Government of the Russian Federation, Deputy Head of the Government Department of the Russian Federation.
Since December 27, 2011 - the Minister of the Russian Federation is the head of the Government Office of the Russian Federation.
On May 22, 2012, he was appointed Deputy Head of the Presidential Administration of the Russian Federation.
He is fluent in English and Japanese.
