It’s also not just an act of gathering lovers – it has an emotional meaning: older vinyl buyers are slightly more likely to keep their feelings inside (56% vs. 53%) and enjoy loneliness (69% vs. 66%).
But are YouGov’s results accurate?
If this blog was a TV news story, the camera would follow me as I walked down the center of bustling Soho Street, in a modest gray suit and gesticulating furiously before the stop, folding my hands and saying something impressive like, “Yeah, let’s see.”
Okay, let's see.
While the heart of Soho is slowly losing its charm and dirt — hotels, cafes, Paperchase stores have now flooded buildings once occupied by independent sellers — several music stores with fantastic specialists still remain.
I would probably ask the camera to stop for the next scene where I’m standing close to different people in some of these stores and trying to gauge their age and emotional mood through observation.
A native of Glasgow Stuart, 55 years old, whom I followed from Sister Ray (countdown of data: two young women, three middle-aged men) to Reckless Records (countdown of data: eight middle-aged men, one woman probably over 20 years old), in London for half a day to hold a meeting, and walks around the shop for a few hours.
He's a collector, I ask?
“I think so,” he says.
I have about 3,000 or 4,000 records.
These records, pictured above (he emailed me a picture, I didn’t chase him home), go along the lines of the walls of his living room.
His reason for acquiring such a huge number of albums and singles stems in part from his disposable income: he can now buy records he couldn’t afford when they just came out, and buy items he sold when he was young and in the mall.
"A lot of what I'm getting is the late '60s, the early '70s, things that came out when I was 11 or 12, things that I was probably too young to buy," he says.
He agrees that those who buy records are likely introverts who like their own company, adding, “I don’t smoke, I don’t drink very much.
That's my shortcoming.
Wes, a 25-year-old who works at Sister Ray, also believes that many of the clients he meets match the YouGov profile.
He did, however, notice a new wave of people being influenced by noise in the media, people who heard about the return and felt the obligation to buy back their old records.
Judging by the conversations I had, people got rid of their collection, usually around 1998 or 1999.
Customers who once sold their vinyl to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to buy back their records,” he says.
This may explain the boom among vinyl revivalists of a certain age.
What about the supposed emotional importance of records?
It is enough to spend a few seconds in a store, such as Phonica, to understand that record stores offer a comfortable society to people with similar views.
According to Wes, some older customers, in particular, are being offended by the cashless payment system.
Some vinyl lovers may feel the thrill of the digital world and prefer to permanently remove familiar envelopes for records, items that evoke memories of a troubled youth.
“I think sometimes it can be filling the void or possessing material things as a kind of reassurance,” Wes says.
Since I’m a collector myself, I have it, and I think a lot of people have it too.
It's a simple way to take your head.
"We're like their social workers!" said a colleague from the album rack.
An ICM poll in April found that nearly 50% of people who bought a vinyl album last month still haven’t listened to it.
