Fopp, who has now taken almost the entire floor of vinyl, has a much more diverse audience when I come.
There are couples who are over 70, tourists who take photos, teenage boys and middle-aged women.
Although the atmosphere is less relaxed than in the aforementioned stores – the latest synth and sexy pop Wild Beast, not jazz improvisation, breaks through the columns – it’s nice to see the diversity in their customers.
None of them look particularly lonely, but a painful psychological trauma is difficult to establish by standing 30 seconds next to someone.
Eleanor, 27, walked Fopp for a few minutes, looking at the various records available for sale.
