French court rejects offer to demolish shops in the jungle refugee camp
A French court has rejected a proposal by the Kale authorities to take down dozens of homemade shops and restaurants in the jungle camp, where thousands of refugees live.
In court hearings this week, Kale authorities said the state should be able to take down a total of 72 homemade shops where people inside the camp sell goods, from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer to cut or sell tea for 50 cents (40p) or simple dishes for several euros.
The prefecture of Calais stated that these places should be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they carry fire and health risks.
Humanitarian groups told the court that shops and restaurants were vital, saying that the free meals offered by the pro-government association and other groups did not provide enough food for the growing numbers in the camp.
They said that brick-and-mortar shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those in need.
Lilly’s court ruled that there was no legitimate reason to expel people running 72 brick-and-mortar stores, but said the problems of Calais prefecture were “completely understandable.”
Judge Jean-Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Molla said baccalaureates, cafes and restaurants played a much bigger role than simply feeding people who “live in extremely shabby conditions.”
He said the spaces provided peaceful meeting points for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places that was under threat of demolition was the Children's Cafe Book Jungle at the camp, which operates for no profit and offers 200 lunches a day, English and French classes, and counseling on providing shelter for hundreds of vulnerable minors without being accompanied in the camps.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect the children’s café.
A letter sent to the Guardian said its closure “would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are not older than eight years.”
Two charities, Aid to Refugees and L’Auberge des Migrants, said Friday that the number of people in the Jungle camp had risen to more than 9,000 — the highest in history — after a sharp increase in new arrivals over the summer.
