The UN is investigating the use of chemical weapons in Syria.
The UN special commission is investigating the possible use of toxic gas in rebel-held areas of the Syrian city of Aleppo.
All parties to the conflict deny the use of chlorine, but UN Special Envoy for Syria Stefan de Mistura considers the fact of the incident undisputed.
Such statements came ahead of the third round of inter-Syrian talks, which are due to begin in late August in Geneva.
UN experts have launched an investigation into reports of the use of chemical weapons in the Syrian city of Aleppo.
The first information about the terrorist attack with the use of toxic gas, presumably chlorine, appeared on August 2.
Then the opposition said that in the area where the Russian military transport helicopter was shot down the day before, the aviation dropped bombs with a poisonous substance, but in Moscow these accusations were called thrown.
Later, the Ministry of Defense of Russia accused the happened opposition group "Harakat Nur ad-Din az-Zinki".
It soon became known that there were two bombs filled with toxic gas.
This was confirmed by the BBC by one of the victims.
"A few minutes later I smelled gas, started to burn my eyes, it became difficult to breathe," the witness said.
As a result of the attack, at least 7 people were killed, 23 were hospitalized.
If the use of poison gas is confirmed by experts, the actions will be considered a war crime.
UN Special Envoy for Syria Staffan de Mistura told reporters: “There is a lot of evidence that this really happened.”
The inadmissibility of the use of chlorine for military purposes is stipulated in the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (CWC).
Despite the fact that all parties to the Syrian conflict deny the use of toxic gases, in 2015 human rights activists recorded 35 cases of the use of chlorine by the Syrian army against the “moderate opposition”.
The situation in Aleppo is complicated by the fact that shelling of its areas is carried out on a daily basis, and terrorists prevent the withdrawal of residents from the city.
According to Reuters, the UN expects Russia to establish a “humanitarian pause” in hostilities.
The current regime of daily three-hour silence in the organization is considered "insufficient to help almost 2 million civilians trapped."
Staffan de Mistura's humanitarian adviser, Jan Egelann, said a 48-hour ceasefire would be needed to deliver aid and evacuate the sick and wounded to the city every week.
"We have to send bulky cargo from a column of trucks to the area where the roads are almost destroyed, and those that remain are mined," said Mr. Egelann. - But the Russian delegation confirmed its readiness to sit with us at the negotiating table.
Consultations between U.S. and Russian representatives on the establishment of a “humanitarian pause” are continuing in Geneva.
How Russia opened the “humanitarian windows” in Aleppo.
In the context of the ongoing battle for Aleppo, Syria’s second-largest city, Russia announced on August 11 that a three-hour cease-fire regime would be in place daily starting on Thursday.
The creation of "humanitarian windows" is designed to provide conditions for the delivery of medicines, food and essential items to the city.
The decision of the Ministry of Defense of the Russian Federation was taken against the backdrop of increasing international pressure on Moscow with the demand to reverse the military operation and contribute to the resumption of the negotiation process.
As a result of a series of explosions in the resorts of Thailand, four people were killed.
Several explosions broke out in the south of Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people were killed, 19 were injured.
The epicenter of the explosions fell on the city of Hua Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, and there are no Russians among them.
The responsibility for the incident has not yet been taken by any of the terrorist groups, but the country's Interior Ministry has rushed to say that Islamists are not involved in it.
Several people have already been detained in connection with the explosions.
According to preliminary data from the local police, the scale and characteristics of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the military leaders of the country.
The attacks took place at popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in the area of Phuket and the cities of Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
After the military junta came to power in 2014, economic growth fell from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism remained one of the few industries that demonstrated development.
In 2016, 14 million people visited the country, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of the attacks have already been detained, said police colonel Chrisana Patanacharoen.
It is too early to talk about the goals, he added, but the country's interior ministry "is confident that they are not associated with international extremist groups."
"It is too early to draw conclusions," said Mr. Patanacharoen.
But we know for sure that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, in fact they are local diversions, and we are trying to establish the identities of those behind them.
The explosions occurred on the birthday of the Queen of Thailand Sikrit.
The Thai junta considers the protection of the monarchy one of its top priorities, so the incident is likely directed against it.
According to the statements of the police general Sithichai Srisopacharoenrata, the bombs were detonated remotely with a difference of half an hour.
They were hidden inside the trees on the busy streets filled with diners at restaurants.
It is already known that one of the four dead was a Thai girl who traded street food.
The identities of the other victims are not yet known, but they are known to be residents of four foreign states.
According to the Royal Thai Police, among them are four German citizens, three Dutch nationals, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
The Russians are not among the victims of the explosions, the press service of Rosturismo reported.
Local experts also linked the explosions to the August 7 referendum, in which 61.4% of the country’s population supported the draft new constitution.
It was prepared by a commission for the development of a constitution appointed by the military junta.
Voters had to decide whether they supported a system in which the upper house of parliament was fully appointed by the military and played a significant role in electing the country’s prime minister.
The new system has been adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
On May 22, 2014, a military coup took place in Thailand under the leadership of the country’s army commander, Praut Chan-ocha.
At this step, he said, the army was driven by a continuous political crisis and the lack of progress in negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military created the National Council for Peace and Order, introduced curfew and censorship, and ousted protesters and the upper house of parliament.
How Bangkok is in a state of emergency
The Thai government, led by Prime Minister Yinglak Chinavat, announced in January 2014 a state of emergency in Bangkok and the provinces adjacent to the capital.
The special regime lasted 60 days.
There were two explosions in Bangkok.
In January 2014, in the center of Bangkok, near the Victory Monument, where one of the main protests took place, two explosions occurred, which injured 28 people, five of them were in critical condition.
The explosions produced unknowns on motorcycles.
The authorities have stepped up security in the capital and have enlisted military forces to protect the demonstrators.
