The spiritual management of Muslims (DUM) in Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the plenum of the DUM obliged its imams to conduct Friday sermons only in Tatar, in order to force the young Tatars to “learn their native language”.
The administration says that this “does not in any way infringe” on the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
In some mosques, the Kazani say that up to 60% of the parishioners do not understand the Tatar language, including foreign students, migrants and the Tatars themselves.
The Imams fear that their sermons in Tatar “will not reach the entire audience.”
Yesterday, the plenum of the DUM of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the republic only in Tatar language.
According to the Mufti of Tatarstan, Kamil Samigullin, this should be an incentive for young Tatars to “learn their native language”.
“For those who say it’s ‘heavy’, in every large mosque we intend to organize Tatar language lessons absolutely free of charge,” Mr. Samigullin promised.
He added that “the decision has already come into force” and today in all mosques sermons “must be already in Tatar language”.
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine “Shura” with typical sermons in Tatar language.
The Imam, who does not speak well enough in Tatar, "may thoroughly prepare for them."
The DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the republic.
According to the Mufti, Friday sermons are held exclusively in Tatar.
At the same time, in Kazan, a number of mosques previously used predominantly Russian.
In particular, as the mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Burnaev Mosque, Zakabanna and "Aniler".
However, emphasized Mr. Mukhametshin, the management sets the task for all students to master both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
"There can be no violation of the Muslim Netatar," Mr. Muhammetshin stressed, explaining that the sermon itself "is not a mandatory, major part of the prayer."
At the same time, the prayer itself will still be read in Arabic, in mosques will remain lectures and lessons in Russian.
At the same time, Rafik Muhammetshin said that there was no serious threat of the expulsion of the Tatar language from the mosques.
Apart from Russian and Tatar, other languages, such as Uzbek or Tajik, according to him, are not used in the sermons in the republic.
The DUM decision was actively supported by the Executive Committee of the World Tatar Congress (WCT).
The head of the Executive Committee of the WCC Rinat Zakirov said: "Mechets are an important part of our national life."
It would be sad if the Tatar language were removed from this sphere.
He noted that preaching only in Tatar language "the desire of the imams themselves", but in the executive committee of the VCT "consider it correct".
The interviewed “U” imams, who preached in Russian, are ready to fulfill the decision of the DUM, but believe that the parishioners will have difficulties in understanding the clergy.
Both Tatars and Russians go to the mosque.
Many people do not understand the language.
Of course they will be sad.
"We have to rebuild," says the imam of the Burnaev mosque Farhat Mavletdinov.
According to him, the sermons in Russian are closer even to many Tatars, since "Russian in schools, and in kindergartens, on the radio - everywhere initially."
However, he believes that in the mosques will be able to continue lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We rely on God.
God will show us the way out of this situation,” he concluded.
But about 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
They are Uzbeks, Tajiks and Azerbaijanis.
There are many foreign students coming to us: Africans, Arabs.
“That’s why we spent four years in the Russian language,” says Imam.
He believes that in the Tatar language, sermons will “reach a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience.”
But we will obey the decision of the plenum.
The end of the sermon will be different.
But time will tell.
“It will only be easier for me, for example, because the Tatar language is my native language,” Gabdulla Galiullin concluded.
The former director of the FSIN was put on trial
The Prosecutor’s Office of Moscow has approved the indictment on the investigated SCR GSU criminal case on the theft of budget funds allocated to the needs of the FSIN of Russia.
The former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy will appear before the court, which caused FSIN damage in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles.
The Prosecutor General’s Office sent a criminal case against the former Director of the FSIN of Russia Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the Director of the FGUP “Center of information and technical support and communication of the Federal Enforcement Service of punishments” to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court (FSIN).
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are accused of the SCO of Moscow under Part 3 of Article 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers, resulting in serious consequences), Part 4 of Article 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud, committed using their official position, in a large way).
In addition, Kryvolapov is accused under Part 1 of Article 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the SCR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently stole from the state treasury budget funds allocated by the FSIN to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems of controlled persons, so-called electronic bracelets.
To steal the budget money, the participants of the group developed a scheme according to which the company under its control FGUP CITOS, with which the relevant state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets", and implemented at prices that were inflated several times.
Despite the fact that FGUP CITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, facilities for the placement of production facilities, allowing to create a complete cycle of production of "electronic bracelets", five state contracts worth more than 3.3 billion rubles were concluded between him and the FSIN of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, more than 2 billion rubles were found in the accounts of the Samara branch of FGUP, of which 1.2 billion rubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles of cash received personally Mr. Raymer in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case in respect of which has been allocated to a separate proceedings.
Nikolai Kryvolapov, who participated in the machinations, was found unknown origin of the cartridge to the award gun, which allowed him to present an additional charge.
In this case, which amounted to 133 volumes, the FSIN filed a claim to the accused for compensation of material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
