The Russian Copper Company (RMC) is ready to take on social responsibility and pay more attention to the environmental aspects of its business.
This is confirmed, for example, by the fact that RMK has taken on the modernization of one of the oldest and environmentally "dirty" enterprises of the country - the Karabakh medeplating plant.
The Karabakh medical melting plant was founded by an English joint-stock company led by Leslie Urkvart in 1910.
In Soviet times it was a significant industrial enterprise for the economy of the country, and it actually ensured the viability of the entire city.
However, in the 1990s, due to financial problems, production was halted, which led to serious social problems in Karabakh.
In 1998, it was decided to resume the operation of the Karabakh mede-melting plant.
It was also necessary to solve one of the main problems of the Karabakh plant - environmental.
By the early 2000s, Karabash was already infamous as an environmental disaster zone.
The situation on Karabashmedi began to change in 2004, after the enterprise was transferred to the management of the Russian copper company.
The company began to modernize production, which began to gradually reduce the environmental burden on the environment.
This was recently noted by the Governor of the Chelyabinsk region Boris Dubrovsky, who visited Karabashmed in the first days of July.
The head of the South Urals called the tremendous changes that have occurred with the enterprise since "Karabashmed" moved to the RMK group.
The main event for the modernization of Karabashmedi in recent years has been the construction of a new sulfuric acid workshop, allowing to capture up to 99.9% of metallurgical gases.
According to the president of the Russian copper company Vsevolod Levin, the volume of investments in this project amounted to about 7 billion rubles.
The next stage of modernization of the "Karabashmed" JSC is the reconstruction of the converter remodel.
The replacement of three converters, sprinklers, gas pipeline is planned for the end of 2017.
The cost of the project is 2.5 billion rubles.
In addition, at the end of 2016 it is planned to launch a new workshop for the treatment of industrial waste worth 1 billion rubles.
In turn, the amounts of taxes allocated to the budget of the city of Karabakh will increase.
For the entire period of implementation of the Tominsky GOK project - from the beginning of construction to the commissioning of the second stage - the federal penalty will receive 8.9 billion rubles.
And after the introduction of the GOK into operation, the income of taxes in the budgets of all levels can amount to 80.9 billion rubles.
During the year of production in the Varna region, 346.3 million rubles were transferred to budgets of different levels.
And that's for the first year.
“The longer the enterprise is successfully operating, the more the amount of deductions may be,” Valery Ulanovsky added.
The RMK clarified that in 2015 the tax deductions from the Mikheevsky GOK were close to 1 billion rubles.
However, the participation of enterprises in the life and development of the territories of their presence is not limited to tax deductions.
The enterprises of RMK help to repair and maintain schools, kindergartens, sports facilities, to build cultural and entertainment facilities, to improve the territory.
In 2016, one of the largest social projects of the Russian copper company in Karabakh was a major overhaul, and in fact - almost a complete restructuring of the kindergarten N9 for 95 pupils.
The building, built in 1960, was in an emergency condition.
Also on the territory of the "RMK Arena" will be a landscape park with an artificial pond, underground and above ground parking for 600 parking spaces, cafes and sports shops.
