WSJ: The U.S. is considering imposing sanctions against Russia because of the hacking of Democratic servers.
U.S. officials are considering imposing new sanctions against Russia in response to a Democratic Party server hack, The Wall Street Journal reports, citing sources.
To impose sanctions, President Barack Obama’s administration will have to officially blame the attack on Russia’s servers or Russian-backed hackers.
According to sources, the FBI and other U.S. intelligence agencies are almost certain of Russia’s involvement in the cyber attack.
The WSJ notes that the U.S. generally prefers not to name those who carry out hacker attacks.
The exception is the 2014 hack of the Sony Entertainment Pictures database, for which responsibility was officially entrusted to the DPRK.
Last year, however, Obama issued a decree simplifying the procedure for imposing sanctions on those who carry out or facilitate cyberattacks.
Initially, it was directed against China, but it can also be used against other countries.
The process of deciding on sanctions can be lengthy, writes the publication.
Even if officials came to the conclusion that the hackers acted with the support of Russia, before making a decision to disclose the information, they will have to weigh the possible consequences.
They have to determine whether the incident is serious enough to exacerbate tensions in the bilateral relationship.
Earlier it was reported that the administration of Barack Obama allows the possibility of applying sanctions against the state, whose hackers hacked the servers of the National Committee of the Democratic Party.
WikiLeaks has published an e-mail from the Democratic National Committee.
The media reported that hackers working with the Russian authorities could be involved in the hack.
