Military leadership has distorted intelligence about ISIS, reports the congressional commission
U.S. Central Command officials have altered intelligence reports to present a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than the groundwork for what is happening on the ground, the congressional commission said in a report released Thursday.
The interim report of the operational group established by the Republican chairmen of the House of Representatives Committee on Armed Forces Affairs, the Intelligence Committee, and the Subcommittee on Military Appropriations found “widespread discontent” among Central Command intelligence analysts, who said they were underestimated by the American authorities.
The Central Command, known as the Centkom, is the main military administration in Tampa, Florida, which controls U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
“The intelligence documents approved by the Central Intelligence Agency’s top command tended to give a more optimistic picture of U.S. anti-terrorism actions than is corroborated by real-world data from the scene, and were consistently more optimistic than the analysis provided by other intelligence agencies.”
“What happened at the Central Committee is unacceptable: when senior leadership is presented with an unreliable analysis, our military suffers,” said House Rep. Ken Calvert, a Republican from California.
The problems with leadership in Centkom reach the very top of the organization.
The ten-page report elaborates on the shortcomings that have constantly arisen in 2014 and 2015 in the description and analysis of American actions aimed at training the Iraqi armed forces provided by the Central Command.
While it does not contain conclusive evidence that members of the Obama administration’s leadership ordered the falsification of the reports, it does claim that analysts felt that the Zentcom leadership was forcing them to present a more optimistic view of the threat from the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
“During the first half of 2015, many of the press releases, statements, and testimony of the Central Command in Congress were significantly more optimistic than actual events,” the report said.
For example, a Zentcom official has publicly stated that a major military attack aimed at returning Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq’s second-largest city, remains under Islamic State control.
“After months of investigation, this is certainly known,” House Rep. Mike Pompeo, a Republican from Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the top leadership of the U.S. Central Command Intelligence Service forged intelligence documents from the command to mitigate the threat posed by ISIS in Iraq.
The Republicans created an operational group when they learned that analysts had expressed concern that intelligence on the Islamic State had been falsified.
As the investigation progresses, more detailed data will follow, according to a report published on Thursday.
An additional investigation, not yet completed, is being carried out by the Chief Inspector of the Ministry of Defense.
Representatives of the Democratic Party in the Intelligence Committee of the House of Representatives of the United States Congress published on Thursday their own data, which agrees with some of the conclusions of the Republican operational group.
“Between 2014 and 2015, Zentkom created an overly closed procedure for intelligence assessments of ISIS and Iraqi security forces,” said Adam B. Schiff, a member of the House of Representatives, the Democratic Party’s chief representative on the committee.
This procedure, Schiff said, “has stalled the issuance of intelligence documents,” has damaged the morale of analysts, and “does not adequately reflect divergent views.”
But Schiff and the Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House was trying to force Centcom’s analysts to adjust their findings to a “definite or political interpretation.”
Preliminary results of the Congressional investigation were presented on Tuesday by The Daily Beast.
Last August, The New York Times reported on the existence of an investigation by the Pentagon’s chief inspector, opened after complaints from analysts at Centcom.
Lieutenant Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Department of Defense would not comment on the congressional report while the Chief Inspector’s investigation continues.
But he said that “experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and the intelligence services and the Department of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these vital national security topics.”
The consequences of the investigation go beyond the question of whether the US-led bombing in Iraq and Syria achieves its goal (as is now claimed by more and more Defense Department officials).
But last year’s statements cast doubt on whether President Obama can rely on the Central Command to provide truthful assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis points.
The criticism of intelligence on the Islamic State echoes the controversy that took place more than a decade ago, when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker wrote a research article claiming that President George W. Bush’s administration, due to the protests of many analysts, was in favor of a small number of troops in Iraq and not a single one.
Hooker also played a key role in the protest sparked by intelligence on the Islamic State.
Last year, according to officials, the Hooker team came to the conclusion that despite public statements about the reverse, airstrikes on oil refineries belonging to the Islamic State did not lead to a significant deterioration of the financial situation of the terrorist group, because it built a temporary non-combatant.
But the discovery was not spread outside the Central Command, the Times newspaper reported in September.
The then-Centcom commander, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized last year after testimony in the Senate that many MPs found to be an overly optimistic assessment of the war.
General Austin resigned in April and was replaced in the Central Command by General Joseph L. Votel.
