"Generation Protests" in Ethiopia, a long-time ally of the United States
Riots in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced fierce opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters were mortally wounded during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the verge of a rift?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa’s most stable countries, a firm ally of the West with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
In the last week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding radical political change.
Human rights activists said the government’s response was brutal.
Eyewitnesses claimed that police officers shot dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage from the protest sites, allegedly shot at the end of last year or earlier this year, shows how security officers beat young people with sticks when they put their hands against the wall.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights now calls for a thorough investigation.
“It has always been difficult to keep this country from falling apart, and it will be even more difficult,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project at the International Crisis Research Group.
Ethiopia is Africa’s second most populous country after Nigeria, and its stability is maintained by the West.
The U.S. military and intelligence services are working closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy is growing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly – there is even a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly an example of democracy – human rights organizations constantly mention government repressions – the opposition on the territory of the state was suppressed, due to the fact that the dissidents were actually forced to remain silent.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed, or exiled to remote deserts.
But that may change.
“If people are constantly oppressed and left with no other option but to protest, there will be an uprising,” said Seyum Teshome, a lecturer at the University of Central Ethiopia.
All the young people are protesting.
The generation is protesting.
The complaints are numerous, starting with land use, ending with the seizure of power by the government coalition.
After widely criticized elections last year, the government party and its allies have completely ousted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea; the struggle for this uncertain, contentious border took hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less wiped out in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to use unrest and re-arm themselves.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, which have been boiling in the depths of the soul for several years, flare up now.
The first, it would seem, is completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years, a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and Internet service has improved.
Even when the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as is often the case, especially during protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this is how they organized the protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
Over the centuries Amhara from the predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia flourished in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of whom are Muslims and live in lowland areas.
But that's also changing.
“We will act together under a single principle,” said Mulatu Gemecu, Oromo’s leader.
The largest protests took place in the areas of Amhara and Oromo.
Many in Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of concern is the loss of Meles Zenaui.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia’s prime minister for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at recognizing early signals of discontent and using intelligence to obtain data and defeat opponents.
“The current regime lacks common sense,” said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalenje, emerged from nowhere and took Meles' place.
Unlike Meles, who was originally from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say he does not trust the security services controlled by the Tigers.
Many fear that as a result, this will lead to even more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said appeared to be elections that the government had stalled and then falsified the results.
During the ensuing repressions, many Protestants were killed, though in fewer numbers than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts expressed gratitude to the leaders of Ethiopia for the far-sighted development of infrastructure, such as the new intercity train and significant progress in the fight against poverty.
But it is obvious that this did not stop the growth of internal discontent with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhara, attacked businesses owned by the Tigray, and anti-Tigrai hatred on social media is becoming pervasive.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, although it has recently announced that it has closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose power in an already unstable region.
“And it will be difficult to get through this tight rope,” Abdi said.
