Depressive food of depression in the "Plotnaya Trap"
In March 1933, shortly after taking office as president, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down for lunch in the Oval Office.
As a gourmet, President Roosevelt loved fashionable Fifth Avenue dishes, such as foie gras and the Maryland tortoise soup.
His menu on that day was more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and for dessert - blackberry pudding.
“It was an act of culinary solidarity with the people who were suffering,” said Jane Siegelman.
Her husband Andrew Cowe added: “It was also a message to Americans about how to eat.”
Spouses living in Brooklyn Heights are specialists in the history of food.
Koua's latest book, "Ragu in Chinese," was devoted to Chinese cuisine in America, and Siegelman told the story of life in a flat in the Lower East Side through food in his book House 97 on Fruit Garden Street.
Their new collaborative work, The Thick Table, which will be published Tuesday by Harper Publishing, is the story of American food in the Great Depression.
Demonstrating to some extent their own culinary solidarity, they met with a reporter for dinner at Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a tiny simple diner in the Flatiron Quarter that has been operating since 1929, the year of the Stock Exchange crash.
Siegelman, 54, ordered cream cheese and a sandwich with pieces of olives, and Cow, 57, took a turkey, mashed potatoes and a vegetable mixture.
When the reporter ordered the meat roulette, the couple considered it a suitable starting point for discussing food in the Depression era.
“Roulettes were in high demand,” said Siegelman.
There was a peanut roll, a cookies roll, a bean roll.
They were made from the main ingredient and cheap products that allowed you to stretch the ingredient.
Imagine that you have eaten as much peanuts as you need for dinner.
Coe's wrinkled.
"He must have been lying in his stomach with a stone," he said.
In the years before the Depression, the American table, especially in rural areas, was a Swedish table.
Groups of women cooked for male farm workers, and a freshly baked cake was served for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to the starving Europeans during the First World War. The “thick table” describes how the country coped with the fact that suddenly ceased to be a country of abundance.
“It was a time when food became a central, difficult topic for Americans,” Cowe said, explaining why he and his wife decided to write about it.
Just as difficult was the new budget diet: mysterious dishes, such as roulettes and pastries, became the main foods; pastries are “a great way to recycle groceries,” Siegelman noted, because cooks could hide unappetizing ingredients under a thick layer of salt.
