Clinton earned $10.75 million in 2015 and paid 34.2 percent of the federal tax rate
Hillary Clinton on Friday released her 2015 tax returns, which showed that the Democratic presidential candidate and her husband had $10.75 million in income this year and paid an effective federal tax rate of 34.2 percent.
In 2015, the Clintons received $1 million in charitable contributions, mostly to the Clinton Foundation, former President Bill Clinton received about $5.3 million in speaking fees, and the former Secretary of State declared a $3 million income from publisher Simon & Schuster for her book's tribute to her.
Clinton’s potential vice president, U.S. Senator Tim Kane of Virginia, along with his wife, Anna Holton, has released tax returns for 10 years.
In 2015, they paid an effective federal tax rate of 20.3 percent.
“Hillary Clinton and Tim Kane continue to set the standard for financial transparency,” Clinton campaign adviser Jennifer Palmieri said in a statement.
In stark contrast, Donald Trump hides behind fake excuses and violates his past promises to publicize his tax returns.
It is common for U.S. presidential candidates to publish their tax returns, although the law does not require them to do so.
New York businessman Trump and his lawyers called the State Tax Service’s audit as the reason for his refusal to release his tax returns.
“Your move,” Clinton campaign adviser Ian Sams wrote on Twitter, referring to the Democratic candidate’s declaration.
On Thursday, Trump’s special counsel Michael Cohen told CNN that he would not allow Trump to release them until the end of the checks.
Critics of Trump, including Republican presidential candidate Mitta Romney and other fellow Republicans in 2012, said his refusal raises questions about his condition, his charitable contributions, his business operations and other ties, including with Russia.
Clinton grabbed hold of the issue and released an online video on Friday that focused on prominent Republicans who had persuaded Trump to publicize his tax returns.
On Thursday, she raised the issue during a speech on the economy in Michigan.
“He refuses to do what every presidential candidate has done without exception for decades: to make public his tax returns,” she told the gathering.
The Politico newspaper reported that Trump paid no or almost no taxes for two years in the 1990s, and a New York Times business reviewer on Friday quoted many tax lawyers and accountants who believe that perhaps the case is still pending.
Federal tax rates have become the subject of controversy in the presidential election.
Clinton backed a rule named after billionaire investor Warren Buffett that would ensure that people earning more than $1 million a year would pay a tax rate of at least 30 percent.
President Barack Obama also supported the proposal.
At a meeting with Clinton last week in Omaha, Nebraska, Buffett, whose Berkshire Hathaway conglomerate is based there, suggested Trump meet and exchange tax returns.
Buffett said he was also under scrutiny by the IRS, and that Trump was “fearful” not of the tax collection agency but of voters.
Clinton’s election campaign released tax returns up to the year 2007.
The Clintons, who now live in Chappaqua, New York, paid an average federal tax rate of about 32 percent from 2007 to 2014 and an effective aggregate tax rate of about 40.5 percent.
The 2015 Clinton Declaration showed that, unlike most Americans, only $100 of their income was sourced from wages.
Their main investment was a low-cost index mutual fund, and the Clintons reported dividends and capital gains of $109,000.
