The future of the Portland metallurgical plant is in jeopardy due to the termination of the electricity contract
The future of the Portland aluminum plant in Victoria — as well as the jobs of hundreds of workers — is in jeopardy because the power company that supplies the plant, according to one of the plant’s owners, is going to terminate the supply contract: it is planned that all supply contracts will be terminated.
The move follows a decision earlier this year by the Victorian government not to extend subsidies granted to support the plant’s operation.
The 20-year fixed subsidy expires in November.
Up to 2,000 jobs could be at risk at Alcoa’s Portland plant.
As many as 2,000 jobs – directly and indirectly – could be at risk as a result of any closure.
There may also be additional indirect effects, as the metallurgical plant consumes about 10 percent of all electricity produced in Victoria.
In 2014, Alcoa closed a metallurgical plant in Point Henry, which led to the closure of the power plant in England last year.
Alcoa’s Portland-based metallurgical plant is losing money and risking closure.
These actions were the result of reflections on the future of the plant, which have been ongoing for several years, initially due to the strong positions of the Australian dollar, and later due to the price of the plant's products.
AGL, which supplies a large aluminum power plant with its Loy Yang A power plant in Latrobe Valley, said it expects the other three owners to also take steps to terminate the contracts.
The controlling stake in the plant is owned by Alcoa and Alumina, and smaller stakes are held by CITIC, a Chinese company, and Marubeni Corp, a Japanese company.
"AGL expects that the Portland facility will continue to operate, that is, that the physical demand for electricity from the metallurgical plant will not stop," she said.
According to AGL, the contracts mentioned are so-called “hedged contracts” that were to enter into force in November 2016.
The contracts have a 12-month termination period, so they will actually expire in 2017.
“Accordingly, AGL still expects these contracts to bring in their share of revenue in fiscal year 2017,” the company said.
Any potential impact on AGL’s profit from the 2018 financial year is currently limited to forecasts of a strong futures market for wholesale electricity prices.
