NASA's climate model: Venus was once inhabited
Venus may have once been habitable, according to estimates from NASA’s new climate model.
Scientists at NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model for studying past Venus, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine whether conditions similar to those of Earth could ever exist on Venus, with its hot waterless surface and atmosphere oversaturated with carbon dioxide.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus's low rotation speed is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus may have had a dilute atmosphere like Earth's, and still rotate slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
There were probably more arid regions on the planet than on Earth, but once there was enough water and enough geographic variability to create living conditions and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent fainter.
“According to the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus substitutes its daytime side of the sun for almost two months at a time,” GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio said in a press release.
It heats the planet’s surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds acting as an umbrella protecting the planet’s surface from a substantial portion of the sun’s heat.
The result is average climate temperatures, which are surprisingly several degrees colder than they are today on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development previously assumed by planetary scientists.
Despite the fact that Venus was once perhaps habitable, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans were evaporating and its water vapor was burned out by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen plummeted, there was only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect — that is, Venus, as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
