Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiades cluster
The last mission of the Kepler space telescope helped astronomers to collect the most complete catalog of the rotation rates of stars in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how periods of rotation relate to the formation of planets.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age, and even the history of its solar system,” said Luisa Ribal, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the Calypso Institute.
The Pleiades cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in the cluster are only reaching maturity now; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They're spinning as fast as they'll ever be.
At their peak speeds of rotation, these adult stars throw out large amounts of stellar wind.
When traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds have a braking effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its speed of rotation begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation speed of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable starspots, such as sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotation speeds suggests that more massive stars are spinning at a slower rate than less massive stars.
Ribal compares the stars to the dancers: the larger ones make the pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades, we observe that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, while those that rotate faster are usually very light stars," Riball said.
Since the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with the rotation rates.
"The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both younger and older," said Riball.
We want to know more about how, where and why stars slow their rotation and hang their "dance shoes" on the nail, figuratively speaking.
Riball and her colleagues detailed their latest analysis of the Pleiades rotation speeds in three new papers that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
