Contrary to the international trend of rising inequality, it is declining in Namibia.
In comparison with the 1993 figure, the Gini coefficient, which is the standard indicator of income inequality, fell by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
The poverty rate fell from 69 per cent in 1993 to less than 30 per cent.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $1.90 a day) has also declined, from nearly 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has Africa’s highest free speech rating, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country far ahead of the United States and other wealthy states.
