Even now, with commodity prices falling, Namibia is able to maintain a high growth rate.
At the same time, the debt-to-GDP ratio is about 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the debt level in the U.S. and most European countries.
Of course, Namibia has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least according to traditional assessment methods, is still quite high – almost 28 per cent.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high rate of HIV/AIDS - almost 17% of the population is infected.
According to the World Bank, Namibia is one of the countries with above-average incomes, but the authorities insist that their state is in fact a developing country.
Namibia, of course, faces some of the difficulties that are inherent in underdeveloped economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
On the territory of the country, isolated nomadic tribes of hunter-gatherers live in the deserts, which in one way or another must be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
Integrating people who were on the periphery of the world economy a quarter of a century ago is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, this is even more difficult: just like any other country in the world, it faces the consequences of climate change.
However, Namibia has not thought to give up, the country is solving the problems facing it.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities were engaged in the creation of a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
It is remarkable that competing political factions have come together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap medical care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbors.
About 15-20% of visitors to medical institutions in the northern areas of Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia is talking about building a wall that would separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
The Namibians understood that the neighbors were not chosen, and therefore decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, take part in regional medical projects, encourage investment and exchange students.
In addition, the Government of Namibia has rightly held that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of the few at the expense of the many.
The authorities understand that the income from Namibia’s natural resources needs to be invested in infrastructure and production facilities.
They are also aware that it would be irresponsible not to seek to maximize profits from the sale of the country’s resources, and are reviewing investment laws and mining contracts to make sure that this is the case.
Transparency is crucial to this process, so strong government support for freedom of speech is so important.
As the head of state Hague Gyeongbok noted, the media often say what he does not like.
But after fighting for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must protect the freedoms it has gained, the president said.
Not all of Namibia ' s key resources are inexhaustible.
Some, such as fisheries, are renewable, and the Government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year, more than a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that begin with serious shortcomings – racism, colonialism, inequality and low levels of development – can find themselves on the path to common prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and imitation.
Many have heard of the "Golden Varna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps this was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts were found - more than three thousand total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only one burial site, known as Grave No. 43, extracted 990 gold objects weighing more than 1.5 kg.
However, the official status of the world’s oldest gold may soon shift to the opaque-looking berry found by archaeologists in July of this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yunatitsi.
Unlike Varna, the port city, Tell Yunatitsi is located far from the sea, near the village Yunatitsi Pazardzhik district.
The bead is a golden stripe turned into a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiev, the head of excavations at Tella Yunatsit, dated the find 4600 BC and stated that it is older than the gold of Varna for at least 200 years.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date from about the same period, 4600 - 4200 BC.
Technologies that allow the metal to be dated with perfect accuracy do not currently exist.
How do you know which gold is older?
Apparently, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: “I am absolutely sure that Yunats’ gold is older than Varna’s gold.”
It is a finding of extreme importance: in view it is a tiny object, but it is large enough to take a proper place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiev said that in the near future, scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as repeatedly and more carefully study the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the berry with as much accuracy as possible.
The location also explains a lot.
Tell Yunatitsi is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Today, Tell Yunatitsi is considered to be the oldest “city” in Europe.
Tell was founded by descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
During the following centuries, metalworking developed rapidly in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the national historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: the Balkan-Carpathian metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC, urban-type settlements began to appear around metalworking centers.
They are now called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Yunatitsi is perhaps the most ancient, as artifacts from 4900 BC were found here.
I would call Tell Yunatize a prototype of a modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
“This place is a thousand years older than Sumer,” says Boyadjiev, referring to the commonly held view that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia – modern Iraq.
There were the first cities in the usual sense of the word.
Excavations of Tella Yunatsi have been going on since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
Remains of the fortress wall, which once reached three meters in height, were found.
There is little left of the houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish between streets, public buildings, urban dense construction, "business center" and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunatsi is often called the "Bird City": dozens of clay figures of birds were found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but an object of local worship.
The "Bird's City" was destroyed around 4100 BC - possibly by Indo-European tribes who came from the northeast.
The nomads had no cities, but they had horses and weapons.
The three-metre walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of a brutal massacre: inside the houses were found the remains of old men, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by battle axes.
New findings and new facts appear annually, changing the usual notions of ancient human history.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the “lost” first civilization of Europe, which originated in the Balkans.
A powerful stimulus in the search for this civilization was the “gold of Varna”, found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that the golden luxury of Varna should have preceded something - something like a tiny gold bean created in Tella Yunatsit.
